__data__.text: Peter Pan was a fictional character created by J. M. Barrie. J. M. Barrie was a Scottish novelist and playwright.

A free-spirited and mischievous young boy could fly, never growing up, Peter Pan spent his never-ending childhood having adventures on the mythical island of Neverland as the leader of the Lost Boys. The Lost Boys were led by Peter Pan. Peter Pan interacted with fairies. Fairies interacted with Peter Pan.
Peter Pan interacted with pirates. Pirates interacted with Peter Pan. Peter Pan interacted with mermaids.
Mermaids interacted with Peter Pan.
Peter Pan occasionally interacted with ordinary children from the world outside Neverland.
Neverland is a mythical island where Peter Pan has adventures. Peter Pan has become a cultural icon symbolizing youthful innocence and escapism.

Barrie wrote two distinct works: The Little White Bird (1902) with chapters 13–18 published in Peter Pan in Kensington Gardens in 1906, and the West End stage play Peter Pan; or, the Boy Who Wouldn't Grow Up (1904).

The character of Peter Pan has been featured in various media and merchandise beyond Barrie's works. Several films based on Peter Pan have been produced, including adaptations and expansions of Barrie's original stories. A television series featuring Peter Pan has also been produced, further expanding on the character's mythology. Additional works, such as novels, comics, and other merchandise, have been created to celebrate and explore the world of Peter Pan.
